a and why his pro-democracy message still matters. From 1914 to 1966, Gold produced a body of literature best defined as "the direct expression of a man who is angry about something"—the injustices of American society. From his early support for radical leaders like John Reed and solidarity with impoverished immigrants and exploited workers, to his determined support for the Civil Rights movement and opposition to the Vietnam War, Damned Agitator shows how Gold directed his righteous indignation to advocate for those who were least able to advocate for themselves. This collection is the first to include the full range of Gold's writings, from poetry, fiction, and drama to literary criticism, personal memoir, and social commentary. At a time when democracy is threatened worldwide, Michael Gold is freshly relevant to a new generation. Though his legacy has been largely erased, this book recovers the deep political passions of the "damned agitator."  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 4aCultural Studies : Cultural Studies. 4aHistory : American Labor History. 4aLiterature : American Literature. 4aLiterature : Twentieth- and Twenty-First-Century Studies. 4aPolitics and Law : Political Philosophy. 7aLITERARY COLLECTIONS / Essays.2bisacsh1 aChura, Patrick, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChura, Patrick, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package 2023z978311149193640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978143849535440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438495354423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438495354/original  a978-3-11-149193-6  SUNY Press eBook Package 2023b2023  aGBV-deGruyter-alles